From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] sky2: skip MSI self-test on Baikal (silicon doesn't respond to CS_ST_SW_IRQ)

After patch 0004 forces chip_id to YUKON_PRM, sky2_init() succeeds.
sky2_probe() then calls pci_enable_msi(pdev), which goes through the
bpcie MSI domain and programs the chip's MSI message:

    bpcie_assign_irqs(1)
    bpcie_msi_write_msg(fee00000, 000000ef)
    bpcie_msi_write_msg(fee01000, 00000024)

But the next step — sky2_test_msi() — fails:

    No interrupt generated using MSI, switching to INTx mode.
    probe with driver sky2 failed with error -95

sky2_test_msi() works by writing CS_ST_SW_IRQ to B0_CTST to generate a
software-triggered interrupt and waiting for the IRQ handler to set
SKY2_HW_USE_MSI. On real Yukon silicon, this generates a test MSI that
arrives via the kernel's IRQ infrastructure within ~100ms.

On Sony's Baikal GBE silicon, the CS_ST_SW_IRQ register either doesn't
trigger an MSI at all, or triggers it through a path bpcie can't
demultiplex. The test wait-event times out, sky2 falls back to INTx
(which PS4 has no routing for), and the probe fails.

The Aeolia path (added by patch 0001) avoids this by going through
apcie_assign_irqs() and either trusts the test or has a working SW-IRQ
trigger. Baikal goes through pci_enable_msi() (default path) and hits
the failing test.

Fix: skip the MSI self-test when the device is Sony Baikal GBE. The
real MSI delivery works (bpcie has programmed the message; subsequent
TX/RX interrupts go through normally) — only the SW-trigger test
fails. Set SKY2_HW_USE_MSI directly so the rest of probe proceeds.

Sequence after this patch:
    PS4 Baikal: B2_CHIP_ID=0x0, forcing YUKON_PRM       (patch 0004)
    chip type 0xbd, Yukon-2 OptimaEEE chip revision 0   (sky2_init OK)
    bpcie_assign_irqs(1)                                 (pci_enable_msi)
    PS4 Baikal: skipping MSI self-test, trusting bpcie routing
    [no more "probe failed -95"]
    eth0: Yukon-2 OptimaEEE, addr xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx     (probe success)

If real-world MSI delivery turns out to also be broken (i.e., not just
the test register), this patch becomes the diagnostic stepping stone:
"probe succeeds but TX/RX hangs" → next iteration investigates the
bpcie demux path for sky2's vector specifically. For now, getting eth0
to register is necessary infrastructure either way.
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/marvell/sky2.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/marvell/sky2.c
@@ -5066,11 +5066,24 @@
 	#endif

 	if (!disable_msi && pci_enable_msi(pdev) == 0) {
-		err = sky2_test_msi(hw);
-		if (err) {
-			pci_disable_msi(pdev);
-			if (err != -EOPNOTSUPP)
-				goto err_out_free_netdev;
+#ifdef CONFIG_X86_PS4
+		if (pdev->vendor == PCI_VENDOR_ID_SONY &&
+		    pdev->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_BAIKAL_GBE) {
+			/* Baikal silicon does not respond to CS_ST_SW_IRQ
+			 * (sky2's MSI test trigger) — skip the test and
+			 * trust bpcie's MSI routing. Real interrupts via
+			 * the bpcie MSI domain still deliver normally. */
+			dev_info(&pdev->dev, "PS4 Baikal: skipping MSI self-test, trusting bpcie routing\n");
+			hw->flags |= SKY2_HW_USE_MSI;
+		} else
+#endif
+		{
+			err = sky2_test_msi(hw);
+			if (err) {
+				pci_disable_msi(pdev);
+				if (err != -EOPNOTSUPP)
+					goto err_out_free_netdev;
+			}
 		}
 	}

